      <div class="msgContentFrame"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig">Depends on the situation. <br /> <br />In Party i would imagine casting on this order. <br />Silence if the mob is mage type. <br />Dia (if the mob hits weak but strong defense) or Bio (if the mob has weak def but strong attack), select 1. <br />Slow to make the mob attack less the tank, <br />Paralyze to make the mob attack less <br />Blind Make the mob accuracy down <br />Absorb EVA/ATK/DEF are next to cast <br />Sacrifice for extra healing and regen. <br />Gravity if the mob always runs away or for links. <br /> <br />Of course some of those spells are not in your level yet, so just ignore them until you have it. <br />I think prioritizing accuracy before potency is always a good path. <br /></div></div> <br /> <br />Nicely done ^^  This is a great hierarchy and explanation of each spells function and situational use.  In a party setting, this priority list is pretty damn spot on.  The goal is to enfeeble any mob into becoming an SP dispenser / punching bag. <br /> <br />Everyone approaches solo play a little bit differently.  It's also very dependent upon what type of mob you are fighting.  When I solo, I keep things as boring and mindless as possible (so I can chat w/ GF or watch TV or whatever in the background).  I spam PD, Damnation when it's up, buff myself and heal as necessary.  That's it.   <br /> <br />Hang in there...I had the same frustrations in re limited action points, but once you hit the teens, things start to open up a little bit.  Don't forget that you can load up action bar 2 and 3 with abilities and cast those spells with a macro without needed to scroll to action bar 2 or 3.   <br /> <br /> <br /><div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div>MUTED</div></div>
